If any of you finish the pre work and want to be more prepared for the topics in this course which tend to trip students up :

<https://www.khanacademy.org/math/statistics-probability> - lots of useful components on this course- highly recommended self paced learning to prepare anyone who is not completely confident with applying statistics

<https://guides.github.com/activities/hello-world/> we will be using github for collaborative projects but also day to day, to share resources and for you to store and submit your labwork. income: Customer income

monthly_premium_auto: Monthly premium
months_since_last_claim: Last customer claim
months_since_policy_inception: Policy Inception
number_of_open_complaints: Open claims
number_of_policies: Number policies
policy_type: Policy type
policy: Policy
renew_offer_type: Renew
sales_channel: Sales channel (customer-company first contact)
total_claim_amount: Claims amount
vehicle_class: Vehicle class
vehicle_size: Vehicle size

Here's the instruction for MySQL Workbench. It comes as a "full package", meaning a "sql dumpfile" (we don't have to care about seperated data & schema files)
1. Download the `mysql_dump.sql` from <https://github.com/ironhack-edu/data_case_study_2/blob/master/mysql_dump.sql|here> (rightclick on Download, "Save link as...")
2. In your Workbench, go on *Server* -> *Data Import* :one:*.* Select the Option "*Import from Self-Contained File*" :two:, select in the field there the path to your `mysql_dump.sql` file you downloaded.
3. Press on *Start Import,* :three: (that field might be hidden a bit. you might need to maximize your Workbench window). Import should take a couple of seconds
4. press the Refresh Button in the _Schemas_ field :four: . The bank database should then appear there

```-- 7 find the movies that the most profitable customer has rented

SELECT 
    film_id, title, amount
FROM
    film
        JOIN
    inventory USING (film_id)
        JOIN
    rental USING (inventory_id)
        JOIN
    payment USING (rental_id)
WHERE
    rental.customer_id = (SELECT 
            customer_id
        FROM
            customer
                JOIN
            payment USING (customer_id)
        GROUP BY customer_id
        ORDER BY SUM(amount) DESC
        LIMIT 1)
ORDER BY rental_date DESC
;```

good morning <!channel>! welcome to day 2 of your mid bootcamp project.
• Enjoy learning as you code and today, try focusing on 1 or 2 *specific data questions* as you are analysing your data. Remember questions generally start with a where, who, what, why, when or how.  These can be represented and explored with charts and within dashboards. 
• As you create these charts, consider the *visual best practices* we covered in week 2 - I would recommend returning to the slides to see if there were some steps that could be taken to better visually communicate the insight
• An assumption of a relationship, eg. “this data will be correlated with this other data”, is something I often see students starting with. This is a *hypothesis*, you start from a null hypothesis, and in order to prove that relationship, data analysts would conduct robust statistical tests. You must also consider bias, that your sample may not be representative and include confidence bands to represent uncertainty.

Found the problem - took me a while to work it out ! you apply a logarithmic scaler with a function to the price field - price is what you’re trying to predict, and should not be scaled if you want to draw any meaningful conclusions with price later on (which is what I did with the MAE - remember i said this was how many dollars off the real price my model was. By scaling the price you put a maths barrier between yourselves and the real sale prices, so your MAE is now tiny, because its about the difference between scaled predictions and scaled actuals… ie, the proportion of error is the same, but the number is not easily relatable to $price, which should be left unscaled, ideally.

in essence, by rescaling you convert a figure like $350k to 12.34 and then the prediction is 11.6 - well in real life that might equate to $80K difference, but how to tell ? you would have to reverse the logarithmic scaler, before working out the MAE

** FEEDBACK on the lab - real estate data predictions **

overall most of you made a good job with this lab. But what we were looking for was at least 3 iterations - and its a shame that we spent a lot of time running through this lab in other lectures, and Miguel did a run through of the lab in class on Wednesday, but I saw many jupyter notebooks that had obviously not been revisited and improved. Remember data analysis is an iterative process - next week you will be building on a notebook every day for the music recommender, so you wont have any choice in adopting this practice!

The best I saw on this lab came from <@U0225RHK6Q1> <@U021T7DU0BC> <@U021ZC6JR28> <@U0225RGM941> <@U022VC1JD29> :tada:

• things to avoid : 
_It is generally better not to scale your dependent variable, ie the thing you want to predict. In this case that was the *price* column. If you scale that price, then any prediction array you create is hard to make sense of, and the metrics eg MAE become very divorced from the real problem._ 

_In some data problems removing the outliers can make your model perform worse with linear regression. Something to watch for!_

_some of you dropped any columns that show correlation - instead, you can identify the highly correlated pairs and drop one from each pair._ 

• things to do more of: 
_visualise your data! Especially important to visualise the distributions of each column before and after applying any scaling or log transformation. This tells you if your method was successful because you can see how the shape of your data has changed. Visualise does not just mean do the correlation matrix!_ :face_palm:

_In the EDA stage, identify the clean and wrangling steps and write down directly in the notebook what you have planned to do, to return to later_ :white_check_mark:

_Annotate the cells in your notebook - this is best practice. Next week I will do more of this in class, so I hope to see you copying this--- imagine that someone (like me!) has to try to understand your notebook afterwards, and be sympathetic!_ :pencil2:

_Maybe get in the habit of naming your iterations eg It1,It2,It3, and thus X_it3,y_it3… this avoids confusion when returning to one of your models later_:building_construction:

_Summarise at the end of your notebook - how accurate was each iteration, and compare them. You can do that visually or just in a markdown cell. It makes it much easier for us to review, but also I gave you a placeholder in the outlier for this - don’t leave it empty!_:fire_extinguisher:

note book from todays NLP taster classes - remember that your steps will depend on your scenario and your data - think about what the data contains and what you would like to do with it, eventually, and this will prescribe your cleaning /wrangling steps, the tools you want to use and the methods for analysis

tools we used today in class were :
• <http://docx2txt.sourceforge.net/|docx2txt> - converts anything in MS word format into flat text - if you were web scraping you would use beautiful soup instead of a doc converter, and depending on the type of text you are accessing - you can find similar tools to convert <https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/working-with-pdf-files-in-python/|pdf> 
• <https://www.nltk.org/|nltk> - widely used NLP library, contains many methods and techniques for cleaning the text data, processing, analysing and visualising the text 
• <https://textblob.readthedocs.io/en/dev/install.html|textblob> - easy to use sentiment analyser - The polarity score is a float within the range [-1.0, 1.0]. combined with pandas + lambda, you can calculate a sentiment score column for every row of the data

seems like very comprehensive data and a really nice layout on your dashboard <@U021ZC6L676>! do be careful with re-using one colour to mean different things as there could be a misinterpretation they are related.  we have orange and red being reused to signify urban, stations, traffic and the west part of germany. i think you could pay more attention to your use of text int the labels on the map, axis, pie charts - theres a lot of text on here, which could be cleaned up without detracting from the message. one simple thing to enhance the impact of the viz is to avoid cognitive overload : save your text for an eye catching heading, embed a question in the heading and think about the order in which someone will explore the dashboard - if you make it intuitive (like drill down from bar chart 1 to barchart 2) then you dont need so much supporting text

wow lots in here Julia! I like the 6 card layout, but i wonder if you could have picked a less diverse colour scheme..? and the overall look is quite busy  to my eyes, with a lot to read and make sense of. a couple of suggestions - can you switch the bar charts around upper right, so the labels read horizontally ? could you make all the charts grey but pick out spain on each one? that could be very interesting - then it would hang together a bit more into one story. maybe have one dashboard heading too?
the other thing is to reorder the rows in the circle chart - im not sure i completely understand what the chart is showing me but i notice that the labels for <10 and <15 are in the wrong order

hi Sathiya, looks like a nice data source that you found! your dashboard feels a little bit hectic because of the charts being very busy and colourful, also all different colours, lots of labels and spiky lines, so its cognitively overwhelming and its hard to follow a story in there. can you add a single heading, perhaps a question, which stands as the dashboard header and ties everything together?. can you try using a single colour scheme of complementary colours? what about picking just two charts and seeing what could be done with those, or selecting and focusing on one pollutant at a time?
 i do like your charts! all beautifully done singularly, this just needs some thinking about as far as dashboarding is concerned to tie it all together without overwhelming us

hi Majed-- is this a good news story, i see, or only partial data collected for 2016? i like the layout and the background, the labels and map is pretty clear too- be careful when using colours, that it is consistent - we have a red for ny city levels and a pink for CA overall which is visually inconsistent. maybe choose to focus on either states or cities?
really nice job hector! i like that the colours match across the bar chart and the pie chart

i would be inclined to perhaps not include the map, as its visually distracting (maybe a scatter instead, which would have a smaller profile) -and to consider reducing the number of countries to only the top 10 --- this would make better use of your space and things could line up better - you have a lot of grey space in the middle of the dashboard! What about a bigger, bolder title ? i think the green font gets kind of lost in here

ooh interesting, cool to see a non european city in here - and holy cow, what happened in 2013!

be careful with inadvertent colour associations - i confused your map colours with the line chart colours, before realising it was a theme choice - the better thing to do would be only colour residential and rural in that dark brown, (as its the stand out worst line), fade the others to grey to match the map, and repeat the colour scale on the scatter plot.

thread for air pollution data- add the data source(s) you have selected and answer some of the questions in this thread - be prepared to talk about your chosen data source

<https://openweathermap.org/api/air-pollution>


• data format is JSON
• data looks clean and would probably not need more than a simple parsing to turn the strings into numbers and outlier removal
• JSON is pretty simple and could be merged with other data sources without too much effort
• one could answer any questions about numerical state of the weather at any geographic point on the planet and categorical questions could be derived from numerical values with a bit of programming
• one could gain concrete knowledge about pollution levels at each point and find correlations between the weather state on different points on the globe and build forecasting models
• as an example: being able to forecast an upcoming increase in pollution levels of a certain substance beyond harmful levels may enable us to take necessary measures to mitigate the damage
• one could easily imagine a system that is fed the weather info through the abovementioned api and dispatches "warning events" based on domain metrics to institutions that are qualified to take action

:github: A github hint, because we're seeing this every time at the beginning of the bootcamp - which is fine, don't worry :slightly_smiling_face:, but avoiding this can save you a lot of trouble:
Please, at all costs, avoid having *nested* repositories. That means, what you want to have is this:

• Folder 1
    ◦ Subfolder 1
    ◦ Subfolder 2 (is a :github: repository)
    ◦ Subfolder 3
    ◦ Subfolder 4 (is a :github: repository) 
And *not* this (nested!!):

• Folder 1 (is a :github: repository)
    ◦ Subfolder 1
    ◦ Subfolder 2 (is a :github: repository)
    ◦ Subfolder 3
    ◦ Subfolder 4 (is a :github: repository) 
Always keep git repositories next to each other, not within each other. So this is also possible:

• Folder 1
    ◦ Subfolder 1
    ◦ Subfolder 2 (is a :github: repository)
    ◦ Subfolder 3
        ▪︎ Subsubfolder1 (is a :github: repository)
    ◦ Subfolder 4 (is a :github: repository)
ok, i already have nested repos, so how to 'un-nest' them?
how to make a main lab folder not a repo anymore?

ok, here's how I would do it:
1. make sure all the changes of the "sub" repositories are pushed to github / are in sync with github
2. clone them into another folder, keeping them separate
3. delete the former "sub" repositories out of this "main lab folder"
ok, but then i would end up with a lot of lab repos in root, right? my idea was to keep them all in one folder
Yes, that's a good idea! But make sure the "mother" folder is not a repo itself
meaning there are no commits in the root of the folder itself?
yes. But you wouldn't be able to do `git any_command ...` in the root folder anyway, since there's shouldn't be any `.git` file.

Sian_Correlation_Distribution_Multicollinearity.ipynb

• Id: Unique identification number for the property.
• date: date the house was sold.
• price: price of the house.
• waterfront: house which has a view to a waterfront.
• condition: How good the condition is (overall). 1 indicates worn out property and 5 excellent.
• view: does the property have a view? and of what quality?
• grade: Overall grade given to the housing unit, based on King County grading system. 1 poor ,13 excellent.
• Sqft_above: square footage of house apart from basement.
• Sqft_living15: Living room area in 2015(implies - some renovations). This might or might not have affected the lotsize area.
• Sqft_lot15: lotSize area in 2015(implies - some renovations).

```def iqr_outliers(column):
    """return the lower range and upper range for the data based on IQR*1.6"""
    Q1,Q3 = np.percentile(column , [25,75])
    iqr = Q3 - Q1
    lower_range = Q1 - (1.6 * iqr)
    upper_range = Q3 + (1.6 * iqr)
    return lower_range,upper_range  

# determing our IQR ranges for lot size, sq footage
lotlower,lotupper = iqr_outliers(df.sqft_lot)
sqftlower, sqftupper = iqr_outliers(df.sqft_living)

# dropping the things outside of our lower and upper range
df.drop(df[ (df.sqft_lot > lotupper) | (df.sqft_lot < lotlower) ].index , inplace=True)
df.drop(df[ (df.sqft_living > sqftupper) | (df.sqft_living < sqftlower) ].index , inplace=True)```

<!channel>,
I was on a call with one of you. Pandas didn't like this query string in a `read_sql_query()` statement:
```'''SELECT t.account_id as accounts, date_format(convert(t.date,date), '%Y') as year, d.A2 as district_name, d.A3 as region, round(sum(t.amount)) as total_trans FROM trans t join account a on a.account_id = t.account_id join district d on t.account_id = d.A1 group by accounts, district_name, region, year'''```
it gives an
```pd.read_sql - Unsupported format character error (0x27)```
the problem is this `'%Y'`  expression in the date_format clause. It can be solved using the `sqlalchemy.text()`  function like this:

```import sqlalchmey as sa

# here you define your engine
###
# define the sql query

my_query_string = '''SELECT t.account_id as accounts, date_format(convert(t.date,date), '%Y') as year, d.A2 as district_name, d.A3 as region, round(sum(t.amount)) as total_trans FROM trans t join account a on a.account_id = t.account_id join district d on t.account_id = d.A1 group by accounts, district_name, region, year'''

# read the table from the sql query into a dataframe
# using sa.text()

df = pd.read_sql_query(sa.text(my_query_string), engine)```
check <https://stackoverflow.com/questions/66529964/pd-read-sql-unsupported-format-character-error-0x27|this> stackoverflow posting

i thought i would give an example plus regex tips if you wanted to take it further

Example : if we wanted to change a column of age, stored as int, with the words, we could look for one value, eg 38, in that column and replace it like:
`data["Age"]*=*` `data["Age"].str.replace(38, "thirty eight")`
another example, we want to remove the junk text that contains that pattern ‘38’ - lets say the string is
*“nearly38 years old”* 
we could use a regex pattern to identify all characters before the string ‘38’ and replace with nothing :
`data["Age"]*=*` `data["Age"].str.replace(".*(38)", "")`
this returns *“years old”* because . finds any character and * allows you to take more than one character - that gives you all the letters up to 38, but includes 38.
adding a ?= makes the pattern  what we can call un greedy - so take all characters up to 38 but dont steal 38:
`data["Age"]*=*` `data["Age"].str.replace(".*(?=38)", "")`
this returns *“38 years old”*

    elif x > 0:
        n = 1
    return n

keep in mind, if you decide to scrape other websites, you can come to a point where you *a)* choose a selector in your browser of - let's say an artist in a chart and if you then  *b)* try to find that content in your soup, you get no results. The reason for that could be, that the content you see in your browser (and the html that is generated there) is already the result of some Javascript code being executed. This content of course could be different (way more html) than the content you have put into your soup. Because the soup doesn't run Javascript.

There are ways in web scraping how to tackle this issue (Selenium, ... ). But at this point it would lead too far. So I would recommend searching for charts that don't run that much javascript where you indeed find the selectors in your soup.

<!channel>,
two things:
• when you evaluate your KMeans model (inertia, silhouette score) and you get bad results (e.g. total silhouette score near 0 - which means that a lot of your observations received cluster assignments quite near to other clusters), remember that KMeans is a distance sensitive algorithm. You need to properly scale you data that you train it with and if you want to squeeze out even more prediction power - even check the distribution of your features and log-transform them. If for example a feature such as accousticness is power law distributed (long tail... )  or a feature has outliers, you want to log transform (before standard scaling) it or use a robust scaler, so that the "tailies" don't mess up your mean of the feature. In any case, first plot the data to get a sense of their distribution
• Also regarding the `StandardScaler()` . I think Miguel mentioned it to some of you already: When you scale your features, keep that scaler object (with the information about the features standard deviation and mean) for later when the user input song waltzes in and wants to be clustered. Becaus its audio features also need to be scaled with that same StandardScaler.  So what you would do:
```# create an empty scaler
scaler = StandardScaler()

# fit the scaler (store mean and stddev of features in it)
scaler.fit(df_audio_features)

# transform your features according to stored info
audio_features = scaler.transform(df_audio_features)

# now use audio_features to train your KMeans
# TRAIN KMEAS CODE HERE

# now the input song arrives, wants a cluster. So scale its audio feats with the same Scaler from above 
input_song_features_scaled = scaler.transform(input_song_features)

# predict the cluster using that scaled array
# ....```
